                                                                                                                                 2                                                                                      CBSE   to give cooking lessons
          OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT                                    
	New Delhi, July 20: Students of Classes XI and XII in select schools across India may soon have the option of learning recipes of Indian and continental dishes under a vocational education initiative announced today.         
	The Central Board of Secondary Education (CBSE) jointly with the National Council for Hotel Management will introduce vocational courses in food production and food and beverage services at the Plus 2-level in 26 CBSE schools.         
	The courses are intended to reduce gaps in the availability of skilled personnel for the hotel and restaurant sectors, and prepare some students for careers in hotel management, said Rakesh Puri, head of the Institute of Hotel Management, Shimla, who designed the syllabus for the Class XI course. The Central School for Tibetans in Darjeeling, West Bengal, is among the 26 schools.         
	An HRD ministry official said the initiative was part of an effort to expand variety of vocational courses. Wed like to continue this process  were looking retail, animation and design, said joint secretary Subash Khuntia.                                                                                                                                                           
